<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>About truckaccidentcalc.com</h1>

  <p>truckaccidentcalc.com is a free, ad-supported reference site for people trying to understand what a commercial truck accident claim might be worth. We are not a law firm and we don't take cases. We exist to give injured people a usable starting estimate so they can have a more informed first conversation with an attorney or an insurance adjuster.</p>

  <h2>Why this site exists</h2>
  <p>The single most common piece of advice given to someone hurt in a truck crash is "talk to a lawyer before you sign anything." That advice is correct, but it's also incomplete. Most people don't know <em>which</em> lawyer to call, what to ask, or how to evaluate an early offer from the carrier's insurer. They get a number from the adjuster &mdash; sometimes a settlement offer, sometimes a release form for a few thousand dollars in property damage that contains a much broader liability waiver &mdash; and they have no benchmark for whether that number is fair.</p>

  <p>We built this site to give those people a benchmark. The calculator on the homepage applies the same framework that insurance adjusters and personal injury paralegals use in early case valuation: tally the documented losses (special damages), apply a pain-and-suffering multiplier scaled to injury severity, then present a low-to-high range that reflects how much settlement variability is normal in truck cases. The number it produces is not a prediction. It is a sanity check.</p>

  <h2>Who runs the site</h2>
  <p>The Click Lab operates a small portfolio of legal and financial calculator reference sites. Each site has an assigned editorial lead with relevant professional experience &mdash; in our case, paralegal work in personal injury and transportation litigation. We don't anonymize our writers; you can see our editorial team and their credentials on the <a href="/editorial">editorial page</a>.</p>

  <p>Content is reviewed before publication, dated, and re-reviewed when material changes happen in federal regulations or in commonly-cited damage caps. The <a href="/methodology">methodology page</a> describes our calculation approach. The <a href="/guides">guides</a> cover specific topics in more depth.</p>

  <h2>How we make money</h2>
  <p>Display advertising via Google AdSense. No sponsored content, no paid placements, no attorney referral fees, no kickbacks of any kind. We do not sell your data; we do not collect identifying information through the calculator. The <a href="/privacy">privacy policy</a> covers cookies and analytics.</p>

  <h2>What we will and won't do</h2>
  <p>We <strong>will</strong> tell you how settlement math works, what the FMCSA rules mean for liability, what a typical settlement range looks like for a given injury severity, and which questions to ask the lawyer you eventually hire.</p>

  <p>We <strong>won't</strong> represent you, sell your information to lawyers, take a cut of your settlement, or pretend our calculator output is a binding case valuation. Those are not roles we can fill, and we would be doing you a disservice to suggest otherwise.</p>

  <h2>Contact</h2>
  <p>If you spot a factual error, want to flag a regulation that has changed, or have a correction to suggest, the <a href="/contact">contact page</a> tells you how to reach the editor.</p>
</BaseLayout>
